ent-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1692773177921"><lt-highlighter contenteditable="false" class="lt--mac-os" data-lt-linked="1" style="display: none; z-index: auto !important;"><lt-div spellcheck="false" class="lt-highlighter__wrapper" style="width: 593.328px !important; height: 313.469px !important; transform: none !important; transform-origin: 296.664px 156.734px !important; zoom: 1 !important;"><lt-div class="lt-highlighter__scroll-element" style="top: 0px !important; left: 0px !important; width: 593px !important; height: 313px !important;"><canvas class="lt-highlighter__canvas" width="58" height="21" style="display: none; top: 46px !important; left: 115px !important;"></canvas></lt-div></lt-div></lt-highlighter><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-justify-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-lt-tmp-id="lt-91640" spellcheck="false" data-gramm="false" data-exc=""><p><font face="Poppins, sans-serif, Arial, sans-serif"><br></font></p><p><font face="Poppins, sans-serif, Arial, sans-serif">Start simple! If you are new to skincare, I would advise you not to create a 10-step routine right away. Your skin needs time to get used to new products, if you apply too many new ingredients it is possible that your skin may react to this (redness, small bumps etc.)</font></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div></div></div></div></div><!--gfsplit--><div data-label="Row" id="r-1692773201826" class="gf_row" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1692773201826" style="float: none; margin: auto; display: block;" data-extraclass=""><div class="gf_col-lg-12 gf_column" id="c-1596783587877" data-id="1596783587877"><div data-label="Row" data-key="row" data-atomgroup="row" id="r-1692773201802" class="gf_row" data-icon="gpicon-row" data-id="1692773201802" data-layout-lg="12" data-extraclass="" data-layout-md="12" data-layout-sm="12" data-layout-xs="12"><div class="gf_column gf_col-lg-12 gf_col-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1653642484175" data-id="1653642484175"><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1692773201689" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1692773201689"><lt-highlighter contenteditable="false" class="lt--mac-os" data-lt-linked="1" style="display: none; z-index: auto !important;"><lt-div spellcheck="false" class="lt-highlighter__wrapper" style="width: 593.328px !important; height: 25px !important; transform: none !important; transform-origin: 296.664px 12.5px !important; zoom: 1 !important;"><lt-div class="lt-highlighter__scroll-element" style="top: 0px !important; left: 0px !important; width: 593px !important; height: 26px !important;"></lt-div></lt-div></lt-highlighter><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc="" data-lt-tmp-id="lt-5051" spellcheck="false" data-gramm="false"><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">What is a common skincare myth?</h2><div><br></div></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1692773201725" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1692773201725"><lt-highlighter contenteditable="false" class="lt--mac-os" data-lt-linked="1" style="display: none; z-index: auto !important;"><lt-div spellcheck="false" class="lt-highlighter__wrapper" style="width: 593.328px !important; height: 313.469px !important; transform: none !important; transform-origin: 296.664px 156.734px !important; zoom: 1 !important;"><lt-div class="lt-highlighter__scroll-element" style="top: 0px !important; left: 0px !important; width: 593px !important; height: 313px !important;"><canvas class="lt-highlighter__canvas" width="58" height="21" style="display: none; top: 46px !important; left: 115px !important;"></canvas></lt-div></lt-div></lt-highlighter><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-justify-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-lt-tmp-id="lt-91640" spellcheck="false" data-gramm="false" data-exc=""><p><font face="Poppins, sans-serif, Arial, sans-serif">I think the most common myth is: the higher the SPF the better.&nbsp;</font><span style="font-size: inherit; font-family: Poppins, sans-serif, Arial, sans-serif; text-align: inherit; letter-spacing: 0px; background-color: var(--body_bg);">Many people believe that the higher the SPF of sunscreen, the better the protection. This isn’t entirely true; SPF 30 means you are protected 30 times longer than if you were outside with no sun protection. </span><span style="font-size: inherit; font-family: Poppins, sans-serif, Arial, sans-serif; text-align: inherit; letter-spacing: 0px; background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.02);">The higher the SPF, the longer you can wait to reapply, but that doesn’t necessarily mean you are better protected</span><span style="font-size: inherit; font-family: Poppins, sans-serif, Arial, sans-serif; text-align: inherit; letter-spacing: 0px; background-color: var(--body_bg);">.</span></p><p><font face="Poppins, sans-serif, Arial, sans-serif"><br></font></p><p><font face="Poppins, sans-serif, Arial, sans-serif">On the topic of sunscreen, we want to remind you that you should <span style="background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.2);">always wear sunscreen</span> when spending time in the sun, even if it’s the middle of winter and overcast. For everyday use, SPF 15 is a good barrier of protection. However, if you plan on being outdoors for more than just a few minutes, we suggest using SPF 30 and reapplying as needed. Remember to cover any exposed areas and wear protective clothing such as long sleeves, sunglasses, and wide-brimmed hats when possible.</font></p><p><font face="Poppins, sans-serif, Arial, sans-serif"><br></font></p><p></p><p></p><p></p></div></div></div></div></div></div><!--gfsplit--><div data-label="Row" id="r-1692781029830" class="gf_row" data-icon